title: Social and Emotional Development
subject: Connecticut Early Learning and Development Standards (CT ELDS) (2014-)

document.title: Connecticut’s Early Learning and Development Standards

Engage in
developing solutions and
work to resolve conflict with
peers

adult help to solve conflicts
with peers

taking turns

variety of children in the

complete a project

materials

briefly

proximity, make
eye contact and

or coo to them

socially appropriate behavior
with adults, such as helping,
responding to limits, etc.

new experiences with
familiar adults

games and other
social exchanges
with familiar adults.

repeated patterns
of interaction

affection or
shared attention
(e.g., pointing

of interest) to an

adults and other
children and
attend closely

and babbling)

a response

differently to different
people. Respond to
familiar people by
smiling, cooing and
moving their body

accomplishments and
abilities

when attempting new tasks
and making decisions
regarding activities and
materials

confidence in a range of
activities, routines and

attempting unfamiliar tasks

made.”)

Regularly
engage in familiar
tasks. Begin to show
independence by
frequently attempting to
do things on their own
even when tasks are
difficult for them

familiar tasks with
confidence (e.g.,
puts on article of
clothing). Engage
in new experiences

accomplishments

tasks and will

with adult support

actions with
pleasure (e.g.,
coos, laughs)

Demonstrate
anticipation of
results from
own actions
(e.g., drops
toy so adult
will pick it up,
repeats action
that makes loud
noise)

referring to preferences,
thoughts and feelings

describe themselves in
terms of basic preferences

May want to
keep what belongs to
them close by and often
will not want to share

Use words
and/or gestures to
express interests
(e.g., points and
says, “Look,
airplane.”)

communicate own
likes and dislikes

preferences for
food, objects,
textures. May
reject nonpreferred items
(e.g., pushing
them away)

preferences for
familiar people and
some objects. (e.g.,
stop crying more

person; move their
legs, arms and smile
at a familiar person)

and a part of a group
by sharing individual
characteristics and roles

classmates)

themselves by first and
last name and identify
some characteristics (e.g.,
gender, hair color, etc.) and
skills

own family
members by
relationship and/or
name

self and others

them as well as face,
eyes and mouth

name through
movement or
expressions

understand that different
people may have different
emotional reactions

reaction of others and own

others

awareness of
appropriate responses

occasionally comfort

variety of emotions in
pictures and others’
expressions

0D386D6AB6A142B883F714A00B043452.description:

and respond to basic
feelings in others

peer who is upset)

respond to others’
feelings and show
interest in them.

of when an adult is
pleased or upset
with behavior

basic feelings in self
and others

and react to
feelings of

yelling)

different emotions
of familiar adults

at smiling faces,

faces)

E3E43E61499444679A9E3F1B67481166.description:
Recognition
and
Response to
Emotions in
Others

and feelings to trusted adults
and peers

7E0A3359C41B47A6B482B9D9F1F75EEF.description:
Express
emotions experienced
in typical daily routines

waiting, excitement
about a favored
activity, pride) through
language and gesturing
rather than physical
ways

communicate about
feelings, including the
cause and reaction to
these feelings (e.g., “I
miss my mommy. I sad,”

Express more
complex emotions
(e.g., excitement,
embarrassment, pride,
sadness) and begin to
communicate feelings
(although this remains
an emerging skill
which is only partially
effective)

emotions through
physical means

throwing. May be
cooperative or
uncooperative and

reaction

basic emotions

frustration,
anger)

expressions,
movements,
crying, smiling,
laughing

responses (e.g., will
smile or kick when a
caregiver interacts
with them. May stiffen
when something
displeases them,
or may turn away
from something they
dislike)

daily routines with little
support, including adapting
to changes in rules and
routines

finds a book to read while

levels of frustration and
disappointment, displaying
appropriate behavior with
adult prompting and support

79CC18537532420A80C7BC33319E4724.description:
Make
transitions and follow
basic schedule,

occasional reminders

guidance and support,
wait for short period of

wanted (e.g., waiting
for turn with a toy or
waiting for next step in
daily routine)

transitions and follow
basic routines and rules

support

responsive adult

desire or impulse

another child has,
food choices)

Show
anticipation
and respond to
familiar routines
in their lives

Respond to adult
interactions,
including tone of
voice, expression
and gestures

head and
frowning)

having needs met

by being picked up
or fed)

strategies with peers or
family

Use strategies
to self-soothe with
limited adult support

With adult
support, use selfsoothing techniques
to calm

With adult
assistance, find comfort in
rituals and routines. May
use special comfort object

at nap time)

adults

self, which may

secure

to being comforted
by familiar adult,
can also get comfort
from sucking thumb,
fist, or pacifier

expanding relationships
with adults (e.g., teacher,
play group leader, friends’
caregivers), exhibit comfort
in exploring more new
settings, although they
may need to periodically
check-in with a familiar
adult

separations without
distress and adjust
to new settings in the
presence of trusted adult

01B271AB750648EB9607582E8492C7C6.description:
Manage
most separations
without distress
and adjust to new
settings with support
from a trusted adult

routine separations from

attachment to trusted

unfamiliar places

preference

adults which

familiar faces

stranger

array of adults in trusted
roles

Engage in
interactions with less
familiar adults

caregivers for
support and
comfort, particularly

frustrating situations

comfort and support

guidance from
trusted adults

respond to familiar
adults and are able
